         <abstract>
            <p>Alternative motives for repurchases of a firm's own outstanding discounted long-term bonds are examined. While repurchases are an inexpensive way of meeting sinking fund obligations, available data indicate a volume of repurchase activity well in excess of sinking fund needs. Certain assumptions about future interest rate patterns can lead to an economic justification for repurchases, although in most cases it appears that the primary underlying motive is to boost reported current earnings.</p>
         </abstract>
